content.description:
Crux is near the top going through the twin cracks.

Start below and right of long narrow slab high on the wall.  Climb up on huge juggy holds to a pair of cracks right of the narrow slab.  Continue to the tree ledge.
Single rack to 2". Bolted anchor.

Crux is halfway up getting out of the steepest part.

Located on the far left hand side of the wall.  Climb up the corner trending left until it steepens then follow a slab to the top.  Rap the route.
Single rack to 1". Bolted anchor.

Fun climbing through unique, varied features.

The next groove right of Take A Shower, just left of a long, narrow slab high on the wall.  Follow the groove up to a series of cracks on the left side of the narrow slab.
Nothing bigger than .75 camalot, not a bad idea to double up from 0 to 3 Metolius.

climbs.name: Live Simply
climbs.fa: Mike Parker, Greg Hughes and Mike Delaney

content.description:
Climb up on jugs and huge features to a face filled with cracks and pockets.  Move left and finish on WBFF when you run out of holds and gear placements.

Start just right of the huge Spruce tree roots.
Single rack to 2". Bolted anchor.

climbs.name: Mankey Rack
climbs.fa: Greg Hughes, Mike Parker, Mike Delaney

content.description:
Climb up the corner and continue through varied features including an overlap until you reach a face.  Go straight up the face using a series of diagonal and horizontal cracks to the top of the wall.

Start on the open book corner on the right side.
Single rack to 2". Bolted anchor.

climbs.name: PB and Jam
climbs.fa: Greg Hughes, Mike Parker, Mike Delaney

content.description:
Climb the crack to a sloping ledge then ascend a right leaning crack to the top.  Fairly sustained. Slightly run out at the top.

On the far right side of the wall on top of the upper ledge locate a left leaning hand crack.
Single rack to 2"  Tree anchor.

climbs.name: Taco or Westy
climbs.fa: Mike Parker, Greg Hughes and Mike Delaney

content.description:
Crux is pulling over the first slab with no good holds or gear.  If you blow it here you are looking at a ground fall.  A very tricky onsight with questionable gear.

Climb up to the big ledge on the far right side of the wall.  Climb the second last crack on the right to a ledge then continue to the top of the right trending crack that leads to the top.
Single rack to 2".  Tree anchor.

Steep, juggy climbing with abundant rests.  Protection is not straight forward but it is all there.

On the left side of the wall locate a fin about 15 off the deck.  Climb up the groove just right of the fin, clip a pin and continue up slightly right finishing on the next tree right of Fred's Book.  Rap the route.
Nothing bigger than .75 camalot, not a bad idea to double up from 0 to 3 Metolius.  One piton.

Climb up big, juggy holds to a face filled with cracks and pockets.  Fun movement over huge holds and features.

Start just left of the huge Spruce tree roots.
Single rack to 2". Bolted anchor.
